Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterAnimals Around Us3
Animals are found all over the world. All animals are not similar. They have 
different types of body parts to survive in their surroundings. Let us study 
about some of these characteristics.
! Do all these animals look alike?
! Why do they have differences in their body parts?
! Can you name any four animals that can be found in groups?
EarsDo all animals have similar ears?
! 
Animals have special sense of hearing. It is one of their defenses against 
danger. They listen carefully to the sounds around them and if they feel that 
they are in danger, they alert the other animals of the group.
! 
Bats and dolphins use their sense of hearing to see in the dark. They make 
sounds which bounce off objects to guide them on their course.
Environmental Studies-421Unit–II : The Living World

You 
 KnowMust 
! 
Elephants use their huge fan-like ears to cool 
their body.
The sense of hearing of most animals is better than that of humans. It is believed 
that some animals like elephants can hear storms, earthquakes and other natural 
disasters before humans can.
Some animals have hearing organs in different parts of their bodies.
! 
Cicadas and crickets have their hearing organs in their 
knees.
! 
Male mosquitoes hear with thousands of tiny hair 
growing on their antennae.
! 
Fishes have ears in their head.
! 
Birds do not have any outer ears but just two holes in the 
head.
Some birds have very sharp sense of hearing. They can hear a fish 
jump in the ocean while flying high in the sky.
Fur and HairAnimals have hair on their head and other parts of 
their body. Some animals have hair covering all 
parts of their body while some have very little hair. 
Animals living in cold regions e.g. yak and polar 
bear have thick fur that covers all parts of their 
bodies. The fur traps air and keeps the body warm.
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-422

! 
Animals like camels which live in warm areas, have 
thick skin and very little hair on their bodies.
The different patterns on the animals are also due to the hair on their skin. The 
leopard has spots on its body. Tigers have a striped coat. This helps them to hide in 
the bushes while chasing their prey.
Animals’ furs are useful to humans as well. We use fur of rabbit and wool of sheep 
to make warm clothing.
! 
Animals like cat and fox have fine and closely spaced 
hair on their body. It is called fur.
! 
A sheep has soft and matted coats of hair which is 
called wool.
! 
Monkeys have stiff hair that are called bristles.
! 
Hedgehogs and porcupines have 
pointed bristles which are called 
spines.
! 
Hair on the body of birds are called feathers. 
Feathers keep them warm and help them to fly.
Environmental Studies-423

You 
 KnowMust 
Government of India has put a ban on killing animals for skin, fur, nails or 
horns etc. It is a punishable offence under IPC section 428 and 429.
Animals in GroupsMany animals live together in groups. Large groups of animals are often called 
herds. They live in groups due to various reasons such as–
! 
To protect themselves from enemies.
! 
To raise their young ones.
! 
To get food easily.
! 
To enjoy each other's company.
! 
To keep themselves warm.
Animals groups are led by a leader who is strong 
and dominating. The leader takes the major 
decisions and leads the group.
Cows, buffaloes, horses, elephants, zebras and 
deer are some animals that live in groups. Each 
group is called a herd.
In an elephant herd, 10 or more female elephants 
and their calves live together. The oldest female in 
the herd leads the groups. The male elephant lives 
with the group for some years and then moves 
away.
Lions live in groups called prides. There are usually 
two males, six females and cubs in a pride. The 
lionesses do majority of the hunting for their 
pride. Both male and female defend their pride 
from enemies.
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-424

A group of monkeys is called a troop. A troop of 
monkeys usually has many male and female 
members with their children.
A groups of birds is called a flock. By moving in a 
group, birds are able to keep safe and find food 
easily. Flying in a flock helps in reducing the energy 
needed to fly over long distances.
A groups of wolves is known as a pack. A pack 
usually has a male wolf, a female wolf and their 
children.
A group of bees is called a swarm. Bees exist as a 
social unit. They make a beehive to live in. In the 
beehive lives a queen bee, thousands of worker 
bees and a few hundred male bees called drones.
Fish live in a group called school.
A large group of ants is called a colony.
Behaviour of AnimalsShy Animals– 
There are many animals that avoid human beings. When they see 
people coming towards them, they feel shy and run away. Squirrels, mice, birds, 
lizards are all shy. Tortoise and rabbit are also shy.
Friendly Animals– 
Some animals are friendly by nature. If you give them food 
they will immediately come forward to eat it. Pigeons, cows, dogs and goats are 
generally friendly by nature. Hens and ducks are also friendly animals. Dolphins are 
friendly sea creatures.
Environmental Studies-425

Key termsKey termsKey termsAggressive Animals– Lions, tigers and many other wild animals avoid humans. 
They turn aggressive on seeing humans. Most of the aggressive animals are 
carnivorous or omnivorous.

Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterBirds : Beaks and Claws4
Birds are the flying beauties. Their body is covered with feathers. They have 
wings which help them to fly. However, some birds like penguins, kiwis, emus 
and ostriches cannot fly.
Birds do not have any teeth to bite, cut or chew their food like other animals. 
They have a hard and horny part on the mouth. It is called the beak. Different 
birds have different beaks. The shape and size of beaks depends on the kind of 
food they eat.
! Are the mouth, teeth and feet of all animals similar?

Kinds of BeaksShort, hard and horny beaks– Birds like sparrow, pigeon, hen and dove mostly eat 
seeds and grains. They have short, hard and horny beaks to break their food before 
eating.
SparrowPigeonHen 
Dove 
Environmental Studies-430Unit–II : The Living World

Hooked Beaks– Some birds like parrot which need to crack open nuts and seeds 
from fruits, have a pointed and hooked beak. Birds like vultures, eagles and owls 
and kites are meat-eaters. They also have sharp hooked beaks which help them to 
tear flesh.
VultureEagleOwlKiteChisel-shaped Beaks– Some birds like wrens and woodpeckers have a long chisel-shaped beak. They use their beaks to drill into the wood to look for insects.
WrenWoodpeckerBroad and flat Beaks– Birds like duck and swan dig up the mud under water for 
their food. They have flat and broad beaks which have strainers all along the edges. 
When they squeeze the beak, water and mud go out through these strainers and 
the food remains inside the mouth.
Straw shaped Beak– Humming birds have a long 
and slender beak. It helps them to suck nectar from 
flowers.
Humming bird

Spear-Shaped Beak– Birds like pelican, kingfisher and heron have a spear-shaped 
beak, which helps them to pierce into a fish and lift it out of water.
PelicanKingfisher 
Heron 
Some birds like the tailor bird and weaver bird have special beaks that can weave or 
sew leaves, straw etc. to make their nests.
Study of birds is known as ornithology.
Toes and ClawsBirds have two feet with usually four toes each, with sharp nails called claws. They 
uses them to hold the branches of trees, to catch their food, to swim or move 
around. They also use their toes and claws to protect themselves from enemies, for 
fighting, for climbing up the tree trunks and for scratching the ground.
Different birds have different claws according to their needs.
Scratching Birds– Birds like hen and quail use their feet 
for scratching the ground to bring out the burried 
seeds, insects and worms. The claws of these birds 
have three strong toes with sharp nails in front and one 
short toe at the back.
Hunter Birds– Flesh eating birds like eagle, hawk and 
kite have strong and sharp claws to catch and hold 
their prey firmly.
(Knowledge)Environmental Studies-432

You 
 KnowMust 
Perching Birds– Birds like crow, sparrow and mynah 
spend most of their life on trees. The have three slender 
toes in front and one at the back. These help the birds to 
hold on to the branches firmly. These birds do not fall off 
even while sleeping. This type of gripping is called 
perching. So, these birds are known as perching birds.
Climbing Birds– Birds like woodpecker and parrot are 
called climbing birds. They have two toes which point 
upwards and two others which point downwards. These 
help them to climb and cling to trees.
Swimming Birds– Swimming birds like duck and swan 
have webbed feet. They have three toes in front and one 
at the back. The three front toes are joined by flaps of 
skin called webs. These help them to use their feet while 
swimming.
Wading Birds– Birds like crane, heron, stork etc. have 
long legs with spread out toes. This helps them to wade 
through muddy water to catch fish.
Some birds like the three-toed woodpecker have three toes, 
while the ostrich have only two toes.
